# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tru-blu-entertainment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] AFL Challenge allows players to play through the entire season, through to the Grand Final.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] It features a team management system where players can be trained up in skills such as kicking, tackling and running.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Sony states that this will allow strategic choices to be made as the player goes through the season by training up key players.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] The game also features a quick match mode, available from the main menu as well as the season mode.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Multiple camera angles are available to choose from both in the options menu and while playing the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Camera angles range from close behind the player to wide zooms showing most of the stadium.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Each player is fully animated, demonstrating if they are successful or not, kicking, sprinting, tackling, hand balling or marking.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] As part of the marketing campaign for AFL Challenge, Network Ten's program, Thursday Night Live, promoted the game and its sister title Rugby League Challenge, claiming it was the inspiration for an inter-league kicking competition.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] TV advertisements promoting both Sony's new PSP model and AFL Challenge were run on Channel 10 during the first week of the finals season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Asides from TV, AFL Challenge has also been advertised on the official AFL website, with a competition to win a PSP game pack including the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] Elsewhere online, Sony's Australian PSP site is featuring a front page advertisement for this title.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] AFL Challenge was universally critically panned.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] He gave the game a "bad" rating and a 3 out of 10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-challenge] *PALGN* said "AFL Challenge is a dud of the game that not even an AFL fan would enjoy" and gave it a 1 out of 10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] ‘Be a pro’-type modes in games such as FIFA and NBA 2K allow the player to create a character and guide them through their career.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Also returning from AFL Live 2 is manager career mode, which is very similar to 'be a pro' mode in the way that you can start from the U18 TAC Cup and work your way up, or you can jump straight into the AFL.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Manager career mode also takes gamers beyond the field of play allowing them to manage the team via the drafting and trading of players, the salary cap, training, the tribunal and much more.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Online mode enables the players go head-to-head in competitive and co-operative online multiplayer.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] During the match, the player can pull off speckies, shown in slow motion from several angles.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] There are two camera angle views to be chosen from: default and end-to-end with two options in locked and dynamic.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] The dynamic option makes the rotation change, depending on the ball's current possession.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] At the bottom of the screen, a mini-map can be found that contains targets indicators.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] As the game has a full AFL license, AFL Women's, TAC Cup and Victorian Football League are integrated into the teams selection.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] All stadiums were faithfully replicated, along with the advertising and sponsors.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] In addition to that, *AFL Evolution* uses Seven Network's score graphics and commentary by Dennis Cometti and Matthew Richardson.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] On 3 May 2018, Wicked Witch Software launched a season pack which added the Western Australian Football League, the South Australian National Football League and the North East Australian Football League.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] It also added Perth Stadium, updated Kardinia Park, the squads and guernsies.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Upon release, *AFL Evolution* received generally mixed reviews.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Press Start Australia gave the game a 6/10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-evolution] Fox Sports Australia gave the game a 6/10 and 7Sport gave the game a 6.5/10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] New features added to AFL Live 2 include, a 15-year career mode, fending off, shepherding and a detailed control over players and on-field maneuvering.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] There are over 60 teams from TAC Cup, VFL, AFL, and various bonus teams.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] A new career mode has been added, spanning 15 years, allowing to manage players and teams from the TAC Cup and VFL into the AFL.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] The career manager mode gives the player control over training, where experience and individual statistics can be gained.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] Sponsorships, staffing, tribunal, emails, drafting and trading are also included.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] The game's existence was originally leaked in early 2013 by several sources.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] On 27 June 2013, it was classified by the Australian Classification Board, listed as being multi platform and the publisher to be Tru Blu Entertainment.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] On 5 July 2013, Tru Blu Entertainment announced the game on their official Facebook page.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] Season Pack 2014 is an update DLC for the 2014 AFL season, with updated team lists, on-field uniforms, player ratings, sponsors, alternative controller mapping, stadiums and a number of other features and improvements.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live-2] It was made available on The PlayStation Network for PlayStation 3 and Xbox Live Marketplace for both Xbox 360 and Microsoft Windows on 30 June 2014.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The gameplay has gone more in-depth with the core mechanics.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Some specific improvements include, faster ball movement and a more free flowing game, improved control and camera systems, and more scope for tactical adjustments.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The possible addition of obscurities such as "behind the play" incidents will potentially add to the longevity of the gameplay experience.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] All officially licensed AFL teams are included in the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] While it also features three extra teams, Victoria, Indigenous All Stars and an All Stars Team (Dream team) from the AFL Hall of Fame Tribute Match.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] An exhibition match, can be played competitively or cooperatively.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Select a number of teams through the AFL season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Select a number of teams through the NAB Cup.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Create and play with a personalised team, from the Footy Factory, or compete in a straight knockout tournament.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Select 8 teams to play in the AFL finals series.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Training mode includes tutorials on the controls of the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The "Footy Factory" allows the player to create their own football player or team.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] A custom team will start with a 6.5 million dollar salary cap.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] To offer better balancing for online play, created teams can be used online.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The online component offers ranked matches and a detailed XP system, that rewards players for good performance in-game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The game features online play, with Big Ant Studios stating that it uses the PlayStation Network, Xbox Live and Games for Windows – Live to their full advantage.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Up to 4 players with Xbox Live, 7 with PSN, are able to play either cooperatively or competitively online.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] Online play features a full-fledged XP System where players rank up and collect badges for achieving set tasks.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The game licensed all 17 teams and 12 stadiums from the 2011 AFL season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The Game of the Year Edition is an update DLC for the 2012 AFL season, with updated team lists and on-field uniforms for the 2012 season, Skoda Stadium is to be usable and the ability to play in The Toyota AFL Premiership Season mode as The Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] It was made available on The PlayStation Network for PlayStation 3 and Xbox Live Marketplace for both Xbox 360 and Microsoft Windows on 6 June 2012 and was released for video game retailers on 12 July 2012.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] MMGN and also GameSpot rating it 6.5/10, with MMGN summing up, "The best AFL game to date, and while full of issues, a positive start".
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] The Good Game talk show's two reviewers gave the game a 6/10 and 6.5/10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-live] While Game Arena gave it a lower score of 4/10.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The ***AFL* video game series** is a series of Australian rules football video games licensed and based on the VFL/AFL.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Released and licensed under the then-VFL branding of the AFL.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game involves playing a game of Australian rules football from a third-person perspective, with the ability to perform the basic actions of a typical player of the sport.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game can be played by one person, or by two players against each other.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] There is also a kick to kick mode, and a season mode where one to six players can play multiple games in a season finishing with a grand final.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was developed by Beam Software, and was published by Mattel.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released solely for Microsoft Windows in 1996.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Players could manage one of the 16 clubs of the 1996 AFL season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was also the last video game in the series to feature the Fitzroy Lions and the Brisbane Bears as playable teams before they were merged.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was also the first game to be developed by Blue Tongue Entertainment and was published by Cadability.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released in 1997 for Microsoft Windows.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] 16 teams were available in the game and it was the first in the series to feature Brisbane Lions and Port Adelaide.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It is also the first game in the series to have commentary, which was provided by Bruce McAvaney.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was developed by Creative Assembly and published by EA Sports.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released in 1998 for the PlayStation and Microsoft Windows.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was based on the 1998 season and allowed play as any of the 16 teams.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The commentary is provided by Bruce McAvaney and Leigh Matthews.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game's music was composed by Jeff van Dyck.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was the first AFL video game to be developed by IR Gurus.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was released as a PC only game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The player assumes the role of an AFL Coach and issues commands such as the type of play the team should play (attacking, defensive, Normal) and when to interchange.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released in 2002 for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game is based on the 2002 AFL season with team rosters.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was developed by IR Gurus and published by Acclaim Entertainment.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It is also the first game in the series to feature a live action intro of AFL games in the 2003 season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] A release in North America was planned on PlayStation 2 and PC via the official AFL website for North America, USFooty.com.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox in 2003.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game is based on the 2003 AFL season with team rosters based on that year.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] AFL Live 2004 includes all 16 official AFL teams and eight stadiums (MCG, Telstra Dome, Optus Oval, Kardinia Park, AAMI Stadium, Subiaco Oval, Gabba and SCG).
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It also included all 22 home and away matches and the finals series.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was published by Acclaim with the song Lost Control by Grinspoon as the intro song.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 2 and Xbox on 29 April 2004.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game is based on the 2004 AFL season with team rosters based on that year.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was developed by IR Gurus and was the final AFL game to be published by Acclaim Entertainment, before their bankruptcy on 1 September 2004.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] This is the next edition after AFL Premiership Edition.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] When Acclaim shut down its operations in Australia, Sony Computer Entertainment got publishing and distributing rights to the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Because Sony Computer Entertainment had an exclusive period with the title, initially it was only launched on PlayStation 2.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] However, THQ released a Microsoft Windows and Xbox version of the game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released on 22 September 2005 and is only available in Australia.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] AFL Premiership 2006 is the tenth game in the series.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] A follow-up to AFL Premiership 2005, it is based on the 2006 AFL season and was released only for the PlayStation 2.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The revamped kicking system requires the players to time the button presses to kick straight, because holding it down for too long results in the ball turning in the opposite side.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] There are several modes: training mode (provides the basics), short match, Wizard Cup, Premiership and Finals.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] A newly introduced multiseason allows the management of certain team aspects.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] That includes things like improving player skills, trading players at the end of the season, and putting the emphasis on draft.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It is a simulation game for the PlayStation 2 based on the AFL.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game marks the final AFL game to be developed by Australian games company IR Gurus and was published by Sony Computer Entertainment, IR Gurus seventh collaboration in the series, and was released on 28 June 2007.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game includes all 16 teams, more than 600 AFL players with updated stats and all of the major stadium.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Game modes in AFL Premiership 2007 are Single Match, Season Mode, Career Mode, Mission Mode and Training Mode.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was a follow-up to AFL Premiership 2006.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for the PlayStation Portable.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was developed by Wicked Witch Software and co-published by Tru Blu Entertainment and Sony Computer Entertainment.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game is based on the 2009 AFL season and includes all 16 teams and players.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 based on the 2011 AFL season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was developed by Big Ant Studios and released on 21 April 2011.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The Game of the Year Edition, an updated version of the game for the 2012 AFL season was released on 6 June 2012.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for Wii the same year as *AFL Live*, based on the 2011 AFL season.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It features more management mechanics than *Live*, with a ten-year campaign, as well as multiplayer of up to 8 players.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] As with the other systems, a Game of the Year edition with 2012 players and locales was again released in June 2012.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released for PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360 on 12 September 2013.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The 2014 Season Pack was released on 30 June 2014 for Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 on 9 July 2014.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] A mobile port was released on iOS on 28 May 2015 and Android on 26 September 2015.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was developed by Wicked Witch Software and was released on 5 May 2017, for PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, with the Microsoft Windows version released on 21 July 2017, via Steam.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The 2018 Season Pack was later released on 3 May 2018.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Serving as a sequel to 2017's AFL Evolution, it was released in 2020.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The 2021 Season Pack was released on 7 May 2021.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game was developed by Big Ant Studios, whose last AFL title was *AFL Live* in 2011.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game's release on Xbox was delayed for unspecified reasons.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] The game includes all the features from the previous game and will include a new player career mode last seen in AFL Evolution 2.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] There is also a brand new marking technique.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] It was released in the Nintendo DS on 2 July 2009.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-mascot-manor-video-game] Focused more on the League's mascots than on the sport itself, the central component of the game is the adventure the player's mascot experiences in the themed worlds.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] Team management appears to focus on coaching, training, trading, drafting, tribunal and budget, while the in game gameplay, covers the actual game of the sport itself.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] The game has more arcade elements then the Big Ant Studios version, but claims to still maintain a fair amount of simulation and options to set the level of this.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] On screen meters can also be turned on and off.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] The game supports 3 controller types; The standard Wii remote, the Wii remote with the Nunchuck and the GameCube Controller.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] Wicked Witch stated that the controls are intuitive but can take time to learn.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] Wii remote shaking is used to successfully tackle or break a tackle.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] There are 4 types of kicks including Drop Punts, Torpedoes, Snaps (Check Sides) and Grubbers but only 1 type of handball which increases in elevation depending on power.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] The game also features a ten-year manager mode.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] Multiplayer supports up to 8 players but does not include online gameplay.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] Players can drop in and out of a career game.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] The Game of the Year Edition was released on 12 July 2012 for the Wii.
[src:tru-blu-entertainment/afl-wii] It is an update for the 2012 AFL season, with updated team lists and on-field uniforms for the 2012 season, Skoda Stadium is to be playable and the ability to play as the Greater Western Sydney Giants.
